Overall Quality has the highest correlation with saleprice.

In [ ]:
plt.figure(figsize=(6,4), dpi=150)
sns.scatterplot(data=df, x = 'Overall Qual', y = 'SalePrice');

There seem to be a few outliers but only three seem problematic. Extremely high prices for high overall quality follow the correct trend. On the other hand, the three houses with an overell quality of 9-10 that are selling at very low prices do not follow the right trend and are worth looking into. Let's look at the second most correlated feature Gr Liv Area.

In [ ]:
plt.figure(figsize=(6,4), dpi=150)
sns.scatterplot(data=df, x = 'Gr Liv Area', y = 'SalePrice');

Three outliers are again visible, this time on another feature. These might influence our eventual model. Let's remove these

In [ ]:
def missing_data(df):
    percent_missing = 100 * df.isnull().sum() / len(df)
    percent_missing = percent_missing[percent_missing > 0].sort_values() 
    
    return percent_missing
